  "definition": {
    "en": "Clotiazepam, when dried, contains not less than 98."
  },
  "appearance": {
    "en": "Clotiazepam occurs as white to light yellow-white, crystals or crystalline powder. It is odorless, and has a slightly bitter taste. It is very soluble in chloroform, freely soluble in metha-nol, in ethanol (95), in acetone, in acetic acid (100) and in ethyl acetate, soluble in diethyl ether, and practically insolu-ble in water. It dissolves in 0.1 mol/L hydrochloric acid TS. It is gradually colored by light. of Clotiazepam, according to Method 3, and perform the test (not more than 2 ppm). Related substances—Dissolve 0.25 g of Clotiazepam in 10 mL of acetone, and use this solution as the sample so-lution. Pipet 1 mL of the sample solution, add acetone to make exactly 20 mL, pipet 2 mL of this solution, add ace-tone to make exactly 50 mL, and use this solution as the standard solution. Perform the test with these solutions as directed under Thin-layer Chromatography <2.03>. Spot 10 mL each of the sample solution and standard solution on a plate of silica gel with fluorescent indicator for thin-layer chromatography. Develop the plate with a mixture of chlo-roform and acetone (5:1) to a distance of about 10 cm, and air-dry the plate. Examine under ultraviolet light (main wavelength: 254 nm): the spots other than the principal spot obtained from the sample solution are not more intense than the spot from the standard solution. Loss on drying <2.41> Not more than 0.5z (1 g, 809C, 3 hours). Residue on ignition <2.44> not more than 0.1z (1 g)."
  },
  "testSpecification": [
    {
      "@type": "IdentificationSpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Identification"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Identification",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Dissolve 0.01 g of Clotiazepam in 3 mL of sulfuric acid: the solution shows a light yellow fluores-cence under ultraviolet light (main wavelength: 365 nm). Determine the absorption spectrum of a solution of Clotiazepam in 0.1 mol/L hydrochrolic acid TS (1 in 100,000) as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectropho-tometry <2.24>, and compare the spectrum with the Refer-ence Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of ab-sorption at the same wavelengths. Prepare the test solution with 0.01 g of Clotiazepam as directed under Oxygen Flask Combustion Method <1.06>, using 10 mL of diluted hydrogen peroxide (30) (1 in 5) as the absorbing liquid. Apply a small amount of water to the up-per part of the Apparatus A, pull out C carefully, wash C, B and the inner side of A with 15 mL of methanol, and use the obtained solution as the test solution. Add 0.5 mL of dilute nitric acid to 15 mL of the test solution: this solution re-sponds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (2) for chloride. The remaining test solution responds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> for sulfate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "PuritySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Purity"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Purity",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Clarity and color of solution—Dissolve 1.0 g of Clotiazepam in 10 mL of ethanol (95): the solution is clear and is not more colored than the following control solution. Control solution: To 5 mL of Matching Fluid C add 0.01 mol/L hydrochloric acid TS to make 10 mL. Chloride <1.03>—To 1.0 g of Clotiazepam add 50 mL of water, shake for 30 minutes, and filter. To 30 mL of the filtrate add 6 mL of dilute nitric acid and water to make 50 mL. Perform the test using this solution as the test solution. Prepare the control solution with 0.25 mL of 0.01 mol/L hy-drochloric acid VS (not more than 0.015z). Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 2.0 g of Clotia- zepam according to Method 4, and perform the test. Prepare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Standard Lead Solution (not more than 10 ppm). Arsenic <1.11>—Prepare the test solution with 1.0 g"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "AssaySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Assay"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Assay",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "Weigh accurately about 0.5 g of Clotiazepam, previ-ously dried, dissolve in 80 mL of acetic acid (100), and titrate <2.50> with 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid (potentiometric titra- tion). Perform a blank determination in the same manner, and make any necessary correction. Each mL of 0.1 mol/L perchloric acid VS ＝ 31.88 mg of C H ClN OS 16 15 2 Identification (1) Dissolve 0.01 g of Clotiazepam in 3 mL of sulfuric acid: the solution shows a light yellow fluores-cence under ultraviolet light (main wavelength: 365 nm). Determine the absorption spectrum of a solution of Clotiazepam in 0.1 mol/L hydrochrolic acid TS (1 in 100,000) as directed under Ultraviolet-visible Spectropho-tometry <2.24>, and compare the spectrum with the Refer-ence Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of ab-sorption at the same wavelengths. Prepare the test solution with 0.01 g of Clotiazepam as directed under Oxygen Flask Combustion Method <1.06>, using 10 mL of diluted hydrogen peroxide (30) (1 in 5) as the absorbing liquid. Apply a small amount of water to the up-per part of the Apparatus A, pull out C carefully, wash C, B and the inner side of A with 15 mL of methanol, and use the obtained solution as the test solution. Add 0.5 mL of dilute nitric acid to 15 mL of the test solution: this solution re-sponds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (2) for chloride. The remaining test solution responds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> for sulfate. Melting point <2.60> 106 – 1099C Purity (1) Clarity and color of solution—Dissolve 1.0 g of Clotiazepam in 10 mL of ethanol (95): the solution is clear and is not more colored than the following control solution. Control solution: To 5 mL of Matching Fluid C add 0.01 mol/L hydrochloric acid TS to make 10 mL. Chloride <1.03>—To 1.0 g of Clotiazepam add 50 mL of water, shake for 30 minutes, and filter. To 30 mL of the filtrate add 6 mL of dilute nitric acid and water to make 50 mL. Perform the test using this solution as the test solution. Prepare the control solution with 0.25 mL of 0.01 mol/L hy-drochloric acid VS (not more than 0.015z). Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 2.0 g of Clotia- zepam according to Method 4, and perform the test. Prepare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Standard Lead Solution (not more than 10 ppm). Arsenic <1.11>—Prepare the test solution with 1.0 g"
      }
    }
  ],
  "storageConditions": {
    "en": "Containers—Tight containers. Storage—Light-resistant."
  }
